name: di-p-tolyl sulfone
Reason: The basic structure we can compare di-p-tolyl sulfone to is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. The addition of the sulfone group (SO2) to the benzene ring significantly increases the melting point due to the introduction of a highly electronegative group which can form strong intermolecular dipole-dipole attractions and possible hydrogen bonding, greatly adding to the thermal stability of the molecule. We can estimate the increase due to the sulfone group to be around +120 degrees Celsius. The additional methyl groups in the para position of the benzene rings adds steric bulk as well as slightly increases molecular weight, but since they are electron-releasing groups, they would not dramatically strengthen intermolecular forces, so the effect of each on the melting point is minimal compared to the sulfone group. We can estimate each methyl group to add about +8 degrees Celsius to the melting point.
